The latest results of the Swedish medical age tests for asylum seekers have been published.The results of the tests carried out using the new assessment method reveal that more than 80% of those tested were determined to be over 18 years of age.However, not everyone believes the tests are reliable.
The Swedish National Forensic Office started testing earlier this year.
The tests allow for a more accurate estimation of the age of the asylum seeker than previously, and were introduced after criticism of the Swedish Immigration Service for failing to determine the true age of applicants who claimed to be minors.
The Immigration Service has carried out 6 880 tests to date and the Forensic Office has now published the results of 2 481 tests, which were carried out between mid-March and the end of July 2017.
In addition, the Forensic Office determined that in 25 cases the person being tested was 'possibly 18 years of age or older'.
In 432 cases, it was concluded that the asylum seeker is 'possibly under 18'.
Tests were only carried out in cases where there was reason to doubt the age declared by the applicant.
Johan Göransson, from the Forensic Office, says the results are consistent with the results of the previous months.
"The figures are pretty consistent, with no big differences from previous months", he told The Local.
Even if a large proportion of applicants were determined to be over 18 years of age, this does not necessarily mean that the applicants lied about their age.
