The Bank of England will keep interest rates at 0.25% .
The Bank of England is expected to announce that it will keep interest rates unchanged once economic growth has been flat and the easing of inflation has ended speculation about interest rate hikes.
The Bank of England has warned that economic growth will continue to slow, and it has postponed the rate hike as the pressure on household income increases.
The decision-makers of the Bank's monetary policy committee voted 6-2 to keep interest rates at 0.25%, a rate hike that has been less favourable this month as economic growth has been flat.
In its quarterly inflation analysis, the Bank reduced its growth forecast for 2017 to 1,7% and its forecast for 2018 to 1,6%.It also warned that the level of household income would be under further pressure as inflation is expected to continue to accelerate to close to 3% in the autumn.
However, the Bank said that interest rate hikes would be needed in the coming years to curb Brexit-driven inflation and that borrowing costs might have to be increased more than expected in the financial markets.
The Commission also decided to withdraw part of the massive economic package that was launched a year ago in the wake of the Brexit referendum.
The Bank will close the Term Funding Scheme in February 2018, although it is now expected to provide more than £15 million of low-cost financing to banks through the Scheme, for a total of £115 million.
The Bank's minutes of the interest rate decision state: "The Monetary Policy Committee forecasts that the slowdown in GDP will continue in the coming years, with the fall in real household incomes reducing consumption".
As regards interest rates, the Bank reiterated that the need to contain inflation would be to "simply tighten monetary policy" to "more broadly" meet market expectations.
The market currently forecasts a first increase in the third quarter of 2018 and a second in 2020.
However, the Bank stressed that any increases would be gradual and marginal.
In May, the Bank forecast growth of 1.9% for this year and 1.7% for next year.
It now maintained its growth forecast for 2018 at 1.8%.
The pound weakened against the dollar and the euro as a result of the news.
The pound fell 0.5% to 1.31 dollars against the dollar and 0.4% to 1.11 euros against the euro.
The decision to maintain interest rates was taken after the lower than expected growth rates dampened the increased expectations of interest rate increases, with GDP growing by 0.3% in the second quarter and 0.2% in the first quarter.
The Bank expects growth to remain at 0.3% in the third quarter but to pick up slightly towards the end of the year.
Its latest inflation assessment gave little hope for households suffering from accelerating inflation and low wage increases, with the Bank predicting that the situation will worsen before it gets better.
The Bank added that monetary policy "cannot prevent" the fall in income in the coming years, but that it expects wage developments to "recover significantly" at the end of the three-year forecast period.
The economy will also be strengthened by a strong increase in demand for British products as a result of the weak pound, which will offset some of the effects of the fall in private consumption.
The decision came a year after interest rates were cut to 0.25% following the shock EU referendum result, which sent the pound plummeting.
The Bank estimates that the overall impact of the decision on prices and the economy will probably not begin to be felt until four years later.
Before the latest decision by the ECB, demands for interest rate increases had become increasingly vocal as inflation increased the pressure on households.
Inflation fell to 2.6% last month from 2.9% in June, but the Bank said it was expected and that inflation would tighten again in the coming months.
The Bank said that the excess of its 2% target was due to the weakness of the pound as a whole.
