As of September, patients can be prescribed a 'reversible' HIV medicine, after the Supreme Court decided a dispute over funding for the drug in England's public health service (NHS).
The NHS reported that pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) is being prescribed to around 10,000 people during the first three-year trial.
The NHS agreed to fund the trial after the Court of Appeal upheld a Supreme Court ruling last year that the NHS could afford to pay for PrEP, despite the fact that it claims local authorities should fund it.
Simon Stevens, head of the NHS in England, called Thursday's announcement a "significant new intervention" and the National AIDS Foundation described it as a "decisive moment".
Sexual health clinics in London, Brighton, Manchester, Liverpool and Sheffield will be the first to start accepting applications for the trial, which will expand to other clinics in October and reach full scale in England by April 2018.
Pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) is an HIV medication taken before intercourse to reduce the risk of infection.
Studies have shown that PrEP significantly reduces HIV infection in risk groups.
A pre-sex medication means that there are enough drugs in the body to prevent HIV infection during intercourse.
You can take it every day or two hours before sex.
Treatment target groups include gay men, bisexual men and transgender men, and people with HIV-positive partners who are not receiving effective treatment.
Clinics will select eligible applicants from men, women, transgender people and those whose HIV-positive partner is not known to be receiving antiretroviral treatment for their disease.
People living in England and registered with their GP may also apply for a trial at their local sexual health clinic.
The programme will cost £10 million and the NHS in England signed a contract this week to procure the drugs following an international tender.
The purpose of the trial is to evaluate the potential of PrEP by collecting extensive clinical evidence on its targeting, administration and treatment.
'This significant new intervention should complement and enhance the existing, diverse and increasingly effective means of preventing HIV', says Stevens.
 Another significant achievement in the more than 30 years of struggle to solve one of humanity's greatest health challenges.
"This is a pivotal moment in the fight against HIV", says Deborah Gold, director of the National AIDS Foundation.
 PrEP, if properly targeted to those who need it and to those at risk, could have a transformative impact on the HIV epidemic in England.
From September, those at risk will be given a drug, through an NHS-funded trial, which they can decide on independently without having to consult a partner, and it will have a powerful impact that will improve the lives of many, many people.
This was welcome news.
"The most important thing now is to ensure that the trial is launched quickly across the country and that no one at risk is left out", says Ian Green, director of the Terrence Higgins Foundation.
The PrEP drug used in the trial has been procured, and we will soon be able to protect tens of thousands of people at risk from HIV infection.
"The launch of the PrEP trial is a welcome event, which was delayed for months by government delays", says Sharon Hodgson, the shadow government's health minister.
We have evidence that the drug could be a game-changer in our work to prevent HIV and stop the spread of this threatening disease.
