The survey found that more than half of young Syrian refugees do not believe they will return permanently to their homeland in the future.
42% of respondents may be thinking of returning to their home country and 4% could not say.
The study found that the war in Syria and the presence of ISIS in the country are the biggest factors influencing young people's decision to return home.
Nearly half (47%) consider the end of the war to be the most important factor in a permanent return to their homeland, while a quarter consider the departure of ISIS to be the most important.
Only less than a tenth of them cite the improvement in the economic situation or the departure of Bashar al-Assad from Syria as the main factors influencing their decision.
Military action alone will not resolve the conflict
Syrian youth were asked what was the most important factor in resolving the conflict.
The majority of the population believes that ending the war is more important than President Bashar al-Assad's resignation.
A fair quarter of the population considers the presidency of Assad an obstacle to a peace agreement.
Nearly half feel that both political and military solutions are needed to end the ongoing conflict in Syria.
Only a fair quarter believe in a military solution to the conflict.
A majority of Syrian refugee youths see ISIS's power weakened over the past year, while a fifth see it strengthened.
The respondents said that the most important thing in the fight against ISIS, and terrorism in general, is for the media to inform people that ISIS has nothing to do with Islam.
Almost as many chose military measures and educational reform as the primary means.
A fair tenth of the population thinks that the most important thing is to create better-paying jobs for young people.
When asked about the impact of the Trump administration on the Syrian conflict, 66 percent of respondents believe that the conflict will not change under Trump.
