Red meat, dairy products, and chocolate may alleviate irritable bowel syndrome
Red meat and chocolate may sound like a nightmare for the digestive system.
However, a recent study suggests otherwise: A diet rich in meat protein and dairy products may help alleviate irritable bowel syndrome.
Irritable bowel syndrome is an incurable disease that affects about 1.3 million people in the United States and 300,000 in Britain, causing stomach cramps, bloating, recurrent or bloody diarrhea, weight loss, and extreme fatigue.
Although people with irritable bowel syndrome are generally advised to avoid meat and dairy products, researchers at the University of Washington found that the protein's essential amino acid tryptophan helps the body to develop immune cells that strengthen the gut's immune system.
According to study leader Marco Colonna, immune cells guard the gut and make sure that harmful microbes that are hidden in food do not enter the body.
The cells that cause inflammation are balanced by cells that strengthen the immune system, protecting the body from damaging sensitive tissues.
If the balance falls too close to the inflammation, it can lead to irritable bowel syndrome.
In the trials, resistance-enhancing immune cells were found in mice that had a specific bacterium in their intestines.
The bacteria in question need tryptophan to produce immune cells, which is one of the building blocks of proteins.
"We found a link between the Lactobacillus reuteri bacteria and the development of immune cells, which are part of the normal microbiome of the gut", says Professor Colonna.
 The more tryptophan the mice had in their diet, the more immune cells they had.
If the same thing works in humans, a combination of Lactobacillus reuteri bacteria and a diet rich in tryptophan may strengthen intestinal tolerance and reduce inflammatory sensitivity.
In studying immune cells that strengthen endurance, researcher Dr. Luisa Cervantes-Barragan found that although one group of mice had such cells, the mice of the same species kept apart from the other group did not.
He suspected that the difference was related to the gut microbiome of mice, the normal community of bacteria, fungi, and viruses in the digestive tract.
When the intestinal DNA of mice was examined, six bacterial species were found in the mice that had immune cells, but not in the other mice.
When Lactobacillus reuteri was administered to mice that had been raised in sterile environments and did not have an intestinal microbiome and did not develop immune cells, they began to develop immune cells.
To find out how the bacteria affect the immune system, the researchers grew Lactobacillus reuteri bacteria in a liquid and transferred small amounts of the liquid  without the bacteria  into immature immune cells isolated from mice.
The immune cells evolved into endurance-enhancing cells.
When the active substance was purified from the liquid, it was found to be a by-product of the metabolism of tryptophan, known as indole-3 lactic acid.
When the researchers doubled the amount of tryptophan in the mice's diet, the number of cells that strengthened their endurance increased by about 50 percent, and when the amount of tryptophan was halved, the number of cells dropped by half.
Cervantes-Barragan says that humans have the same endurance-boosting cells as mice, and most of us have Lactobacillus reuteri bacteria in our digestive tract.
It is not yet known whether the by-products of tryptophan cause cells from Lactobacillus reuteri to develop in humans in the same way as in mice, but genetic defects related to tryptophan have been observed in patients with irritable bowel syndrome.
"We probably want to encourage the development of these cells because they regulate inflammation in the intestinal lining", says Cervantes-Barragan.
 High levels of tryptophan in combination with Lactobacillus reuteri may contribute to their spread.
